Message from the Health Department:

For shorter wait times at our drive thru COVID 19 site at Wheeler County Health Department, please pre-register. You can pre-register one of two ways:
1. Click here https://covid19.dph.ga.gov. An email address is required. You will receive a QR code via email that you will need to bring to the site.
2. Call 478-275-6570 Monday-Friday 8-5 and Saturday 9-2. They can help you register over the phone.

If you do not pre-register, you can still be tested. You may just have a longer wait time.

post_text:
Message from Coach Wright:
ATTENTION WHEELER COUNTY AND SURROUNDING COUNTIES!!! On Saturday, August 29th, we are having a drive-by parade for our girls 2019-2020 Class A Public State Basketball Champions starting at 12 noon! Please meet up at the Town Square around 11:45 a.m. in Alamo and get in line and follow the law enforcement personnel through the approved route. Because of COVID-19 we will not be able to have a regular style parade! But you, our loyal fans, have the opportunity to make signs and banners to display as you drive by our girls as they stand on the steps of the James Stapleton gymnasium. They will have a small bag just in case some of you may want to bless them in your own way! We have waited so long to honor them. Covid has caused us to modify our celebration and our recognition ceremony. So please take advantage of this opportunity to show them some love and appreciation! Join us on Saturday as a participant in the parade!

post_text:
Reminder of the 2020-2021 dress code for Wheeler County Middle/High School:

Middle/High School Dress Code

Requirements:

-All shorts and skirts must be knee length.

-Pants/shorts/skirts must be secured around the natural waistline, with a belt if necessary.

-All clothing items must be properly fastened (shoes, belts, etc.).

-Masks must follow dress code requirements below.

-Neck gaiters must be WCSS-supplied ones or solid in color.

NOT Allowed:

-Leggings will not be allowed.

-No holes or shredding of any kind in jeans or pants.

-No gym shorts, sweatpants, or athletic pants.

-No sagging pants/shorts.

-No tank tops, midriffs, halter tops, mesh tops, or see-through garments.

-No clothing with offensive symbols or phrases.

-No clothing with gang-related symbols or phrases.

-No clothing displaying tobacco alcohol, or drug-related advertisements, illustrations, or phrases.

-No caps or sunglasses inside the building.

-No headware, bandanas, headscarves, or dog chains.

-No body piercing of any kind. (This does not include earrings).

-No pajamas.

-No blankets.

Digital Learning Days:
To remain prepared to move to digital learning at any time, teachers will regularly incorporate technology into instruction. We have also scheduled six digital learning days when students will remain home but still have assignments to complete. They are counted as instructional days, and dates are flexible in the event we need to close schools during the year.

We are extending the deadline for remote learning contracts until 3:00 TODAY because some administrators will be in meetings this morning and unavailable for calls. post_text: This shared post shows how much funding is dependent upon our census. Please share!
shared_text:
Wheeler County Community Advocacy League
June 24 at 9:13 PM ·

We crossed the 30% threshold today! This is, of course, great news as we have been at 27% for over a week. There is still work to be done, but we are moving in a positive direction.

Remember everyone, for each person that completes the census, the county received $2000 in funding per year for the next ten years.

Everything from roads to school books are included in these figures. Please take the time to get counted.

#GetCountedWheelerCounty #Census2020

post_text: ‼️This is vitally important to our community and we are far behind in completion numbers. Please encourage everyone to complete their census.‼️
shared_text:
Carol Bragg
May 19 at 8:29 PM ·

Don't put this off any longer! Visit 2020census.gov. It's easy and quick. Your response matters. Health clinics. Fire departments. Schools. Even roads and highways. The census can shape many different aspects of your community. Census results help determine how billions of dollars in federal funding flow into states and communities each year.

The results determine how many seats in Congress each state gets. It's mandated by the U.S. Constitution in Article 1, Section 2: The U.S. has counted its population every 10 years since 1790.

Your privacy matters. Every employee takes an oath to protect your personal information for life. When you respond to the census, your answers are kept anonymous. They are used only to produce statistics. The U.S. Census Bureau is bound by law to protect your answers and keep them strictly confidential. The law ensures that your private information is never published and that your answers cannot be used against you by any government agency or court.

The holiday is now observed on the last Monday of May, having been observed on May 30 from 1868 to 1970.

‼️WCSS Nutrition Update‼️
We will make our final bus delivery of meals on Monday (Memorial Day). Beginning Thursday, the 28th, we will have pickup at the middle/high school only from 11-2. Pickup will be at the cafeteria dock located behind the school. Please enter through the bus shop gate, come up to dock to pick up and exit out the automated gate. WE ENCOURAGE YOU TO BRING A COOLER FOR MILK/COLD FOODS. Families will receive 6 days of breakfast and lunch per child.

IF you KNOW you will not be home on Monday, please notify one of our school personnel so we can adjust our numbers. We are thankful to have had the opportunity to continue to serve our students and families during this time.

post_text: Sharing this so that all the Seniors see it. Congratulations, Class of 2020!
shared_text:
Cynthia Mincey is with Andrea Wooten and 37 others.
May 3 at 8:51 PM ·

Some things in life money simply cannot buy because they are absolutely PRICELESS! It was such an honor to take the pictures of these very strong young people who refuse to break under pressure even though what they have worked so hard for and prepared for their entire lives have been turned upside down! While we are so beyond proud of our baby girl Keonya Mincey, we will always and forever be amazed at the strength and resilience that each and everyone of these soon-to-be graduates possess! I know I have said it before and I will say it again, I am so beyond proud of each and every one of you for achieving this wonderfully awesome milestone in your lives! I salute you! NOTE! If you are not happy or satisfied with your picture that will be hung in town for everyone to see, just let me know and I will be more than happy to redo them (but we have to do it quickly-time is of the essence)! If there is more than one picture of you, you can pick which one you prefer to hang in town! Please tag students/parents that I may not be fb friends with!

post_text:
Updated Dress Code for 2020-2021:

We know it is early but wanted to go ahead and notify parents for planning purposes. We will have the following changes to our dress code for the 2020-2021 school year:

No holes or shredding in pants (jeans or otherwise).
No leggings, sweat pants, jogging pants, or athletic pants.
Skirts must be at the knee or longer.
Shorts will be allowed at knee length for middle/high, but no gym/athletic shorts will be allowed at all except for P.E. We understand parents’ concerns about the heat and shorts.

Skirts must be at the knee or longer.
Shorts will be allowed at knee length for middle/high, but no gym/athletic shorts will be allowed at all except for P.E. We understand parents’ concerns about the heat and shorts.

Georgia Department of Education
April 1 at 5:43 PM ·

NEWS:

In his press conference this afternoon, Governor Brian Kemp announced that Georgia's K-12 public schools will remain closed for in-person instruction for the remainder of the school year. Essential functions (including school meals and distance learning) can continue.

We appreciate the teachers and parents who have worked so hard throughout this transition. This extended period of distance learning is brand-new for our state and our nation, but Georgia's students are in good hands as we work together to keep them safe and keep them learning.

Where can I submit a question?
From your computer, visit our website (www.wheelercountyschools.org ). In the middle of the far right of the page, you will see a tab that says “Contact Us.” Click on it and complete the form OR click on “2020 Information,” the top right tab on our home page, scroll down to “Contact” and submit your question there.

Where is the best place to find information about Wheeler County Schools?
Information will be updated on our webpage under News and Announcements (middle of page) and under 2020 Information (top right tab) in the following sections: For Students, For Parents, and COVID-19 Information. We will also provide call outs for important information.

‼️Info we were asked to share from DFCS‼️

To limit the spread of COVID-19 and protect the public, the Division of Family and Children Services (DFCS) encourages families to access self-service options online during this period.

Self-service options include:
Apply for Food Stamp and Medicaid Benefits
Visit: gateway.ga.gov (verification documents can also be uploaded and case status info is available for all benefits)
Download an Application:
https://dfcs.georgia.gov/services
Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT)
Visit: https://www.connectebt.com/gaebtclient or call: 888-421-3281 for updates

Those without internet access can contact the DFCS Customer Contact Center at 877-423-4746 for additional information or to request a paper application. Once completed, applications and any required verification can be mailed back to your local county DFCS office. County office locations are available online at https://dfcs.georgia.gov/locations.

post_text: GaDOE Update
shared_text:
Georgia Department of Education
March 18 at 11:10 AM ·

In this unprecedented time, we are focused on keeping Georgia's students safe and nourished while continuing to provide opportunities for them to learn.

Thanks to flexibility granted by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, many school districts are serving meals for students using bus routes or at approved sites within the community. For more information about options near you, visit your local school district’s website or social media accounts.

Georgia's teachers, districts, and schools are working hard to transition to online and distance learning options, and we're working to provide resources to them and expand access for students. For resources, click here: https://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/communications/Pages/Digital-Learning-Resources.aspx

You can always view our latest updates at gadoe.org/coronavirus. Thank you to all who are committed to keeping Georgia's students safe, fed, and learning!

To ensure your students have “at home” learning opportunities during this time of school closures, Renaissance and Get Georgia Reading are partnering to provide readers free, anytime/anywhere access to digital books and news with myON.
Unlimited, 24/7 access makes it easy for students to continue reading and learning at home. Students can read online using any Internet-enabled device, or read offline with free mobile apps.
Getting started is easy!

a.School Name: Get Georgia Reading (type the first few letters and select from the drop-down menu)
b.Username: wheelercounty
c.Password: read
2.Click the Sign In button and start reading!

post_text:
WCMS Congratulates Jasmine Khamlusa
Jasmine Khamlusa, a 7th grader at Wheeler County Middle School, recently completed the System 44 reading program under the guidance of Kim Pinzon. When a student enters a System 44 classroom, her experience with school changes. She begins to see herself as a reader who fully joins and participates in the community of learners. The System 44 classroom helps readers see a path to college and career for themselves through instruction and content that is respectful and engaging. Wheeler County Middle School congratulates Jasmine for this awesome accomplishment!

post_text:
Recycling Paper in Art by WCMS Student Reporter Laurie Conner
WCMS students made “recycling paper” in art class. Here are the steps to making it. First you must cut paper into small pieces. We used lots of scrap paper. Then fill a bucket with water. Gather all the pieces and put a small bit of the paper into water. Mix the paper and water. When you are done mixing you should have a substance that is a light gray color and looks like pulp. Now pour the pulp-like substance into the bucket. Next, get the wood part of a picture frame, called the deckle, and put it in the substance. You then push the deckle all the way to the bottom of the bucket. Pull it up to where you can see it and make sure it’s not too thick or it will take a long time to dry. Now clean the deckle. Get a sponge to press the substance. You can add things to it now or you can leave it blank. Leave it to dry for 24 hours. Now you have “recycling paper.” My favorite part was getting my hands dirty on purpose and everyone had a certain job to do. It was really fun learning to make recycling paper in art class!

Now pour the pulp-like substance into the bucket. Next, get the wood part of a picture frame, called the deckle, and put it in the substance. You then push the deckle all the way to the bottom of the bucket. Pull it up to where you can see it and make sure it’s not too thick or it will take a long time to dry. Now clean the deckle. Get a sponge to press the substance. You can add things to it now or you can leave it blank. Leave it to dry for 24 hours. Now you have “recycling paper.” My favorite part was getting my hands dirty on purpose and everyone had a certain job to do. It was really fun learning to make recycling paper in art class!

post_text:
In January, Kim Pinzón’s Read 180 students read an article about personal responsibility written by Lian Dolan. “Carry your own skis” and “the lodge and back, baby” became metaphors for the author’s attitude about life. When Dolan’s mother made all her children carry their own skis in order to participate in the exhilarating sport of snow skiing, Dolan recognized that anything worth doing requires effort.

Students created their own snow ski people and explained their ideas about what the phrase “carry your own skis” means. “The best part about the assignment,” says Pinzón, “is that some students have really embraced the metaphor. When a student is being irresponsible or lazy, I’ve heard other kids jump in and tell them to ‘carry their own skis.’ It always makes me smile when I hear them using the phrase. I’m so proud of them!”

To read the article for yourself, click this link: https://jmcbrideabhs.weebly.com/uploads/6/4/7/6/64764179/carry_your_own_skis_text.pdf

On December 13th and 14th, the Wheeler County Middle School FFA Dairy Team traveled to Tifton, Georgia to compete in the State Dairy Judging Career Development Event. This competition was held at the University of Georgia’s dairy near Abraham Baldwin Agricultural College.

The Dairy Cattle Career Development Event emphasizes skills in dairy cattle selection and dairy herd management and provides experience in the evaluation of dairy cattle type, production records, and dairy herd management. Participants evaluate dairy animals and place by type, give oral reasons for their class placing and take a written examination. Team members included (pictured form left to right) Joshawa Shaw, Marcy Delgado, Carson Ford, and Trent Butler.

This was the first time Wheeler County has ever had a dairy judging team. Our team placed 19th out of 33 teams in the state which made us 3rd in our area. We are extremely proud of our team for all of their hard work and accomplishments!

Cynthia Mincey is with Renae Benton Evans and 17 others.
December 9, 2019 at 7:32 PM ·

Our Middle School Lady Dawgs suffered a bitter loss to the Montgomery County Lady Eagles on Saturday! We are still so proud of our young lady dawgs for refusing to give up and playing their best all the way until the very end! Keep striving young ladies and NEVER give up! Win, lose or draw---Proud Bulldog fan over here! God bless and Go Lady Dawgs!

November 25, 2019 at 10:35 PM ·

What's better than one win? TWO WINS!!!! Shouting CONGRATULATIONS to the Wheeler County Middle School Dawgs on their hard fought victory over our long time rival Telfair County Middle School Trojans with a score of 50-30! These young men fought hard to pull off this AWESOME victory! We are so proud of every one of them! Keep up the good work! God bless and go Dawgs!
